gland":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Petit","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Alain, Michel, Normand, Mireille, Philippe, Pierre, Achille, Armand, Jean Claude, Jean Jacques, Ketly, Adrien.","French, Walloon, Catalan, English, Jewish (from southern France), West Indian (mainly Haiti), and Mauritian: from (Old) French, Catalan, and Middle English <i>petit</i> ‘small’, hence a nickname for a small man (or an ironic nickname for a big man), or a distinguishing name for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name. Compare   Little  ,   Petee  , and   Petite  .","History: Charles Petit from Anneville-Ambourville in Seine-Maritime, France, married Jeanne Rossignol (Martin and Renée Desjardins) in Quebec City, QC, in 1670. Nicolas Petit <i>dit</i> Lapré/Laprée from Le Gué-d'Alleré in Charente-Maritime, France, married Marie Pouponnel in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1656. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Gobin from Lyon in Rhône married Marguerite Véron in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1692. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Saint-Pierre from Évreux in Eure, France, married Judith Miville in Quebec City, QC, in 1758; see also   St. Pierre  . — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"Pattee","meanings":["Altered form of French (Nord) <b>Pety</b>: variant of   Petit  . This surname was brought to North America from England."]},{"name":"Petion","meanings":["French and Haitian (<b>Pétion</b>): diminutive of   Petit  . This surname was brought to the US from Haiti, where it is by far most common."]},{"name":"Petite","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Celestine, Jacques.","French: from the feminine form of   Petit   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Petitt","meanings":["English: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettett","meanings":["English: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Little","meanings":["English: nickname for a small man (if not ironic), or distinguishing epithet for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, from Middle English <i>littel</i>, Old English <i>lȳtel</i> (see   Light   3).","Irish: translation into English of Gaelic <b>Ó Beagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beagán</i>’ (see   Began  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of any of various European surnames meaning ‘little’, e.g. French   Petit  , Polish <b>Mały</b> (see   Maly   1)."]},{"name":"Petee","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettit","meanings":["English (mainly southeastern): variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Petito","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carmine, Pasquale, Antonio, Rocco, Alfonzo, Alphonso, Antimo, Emilio, Giovanni, Giuseppe, Orazio, Salvatore, Silvio, Tullio, Virginio.","Italian: nickname for a small man (or an ironic nickname for a tall one), from dialect <i>petito</i> ‘small’ or from the personal name <i>Petito</i>; compare French   Petit  ."]}]},{"name":"Michael","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of a common biblical name (meaning ‘who is like God?’ in Hebrew) borne by one of the archangels, the protector of the ancient Hebrews, who is also regarded as a saint of the Catholic Church. In the Middle Ages, Michael was regarded as captain of the heavenly host (see Revelation 12:7–9), symbol of the Church Militant, and patron of soldiers. He was often depicted bearing a flaming sword. The name is also borne by a Persian prince and ally of Belshazzar mentioned in the Book of Daniel. Since the early 1900s it has been one of the most enduringly popular boys' names in the English-speaking world.  See also  Michal ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Michael Petit was born about 1235, in Saltash, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 2 sons with Amitia l'Arcedekne. He died about 1274, in his hometown, at the age of 41."},"et":{"ABT 1235–ABT 1274":"umbes 1235–umbes 1274","1259–1313":"1259–1313","1260–1294":"1260–1294","1263–1302":"1263–1302","1235–1274":"1235–1274","about 1260":"umbes 1260","1259":"1259","ABT 1263":"umbes 1263","ABT 1274":"umbes 1274","1302":"1302","1313":"1313","1235":"1235","ABT 1235":"umbes 1235","1274":"1274","1263":"1263","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","Saltash, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Saltash, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"ABT 1235–ABT 1274":"noin 1235–noin 1274","1259–1313":"1259–1313","1260–1294":"1260–1294","1263–1302":"1263–1302","1235–1274":"1235–1274","about 1260":"noin 1260","1259":"1259","ABT 1263":"noin 1263","ABT 1274":"noin 1274","1302":"1302","1313":"1313","1235":"1235","ABT 1235":"noin 1235","1274":"1274","1263":"1263","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","Saltash, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Saltash, Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England"},"fr":{"ABT 1235–ABT 1274":"environ 1235–environ 1274","1259–1313":"1259–1313","1260–1294":"1260–1294","1263–1302":"1263–1302","1235–1274":"1235–1274","about 1260":"environ 1260","1259":"1259","ABT 1263":"environ 1263","ABT 1274":"environ 1274","1302":"1302","1313":"1313","1235":"1235","ABT 1235":"environ 1235","1274":"1274","1263":"1263","1294":"1294","1260":"1260","Saltash, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Saltash, Cornouailles, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Sir Michael Petit est né environ 1235, à Saltash, Cornouailles, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 2 fils avec Amitia l'Arcedekne. Il est décédé environ 1274, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 41 ans."},"de":{"ABT 1235–ABT 1274":"um 1235–um 1274","1259–1313":"1259–1313","1260–1294":"1260–1294","1263–1302":"1263–1302","1235–12